@NODE "Novitŕ"

	@{b}What's new:@{ub}

	    1) The altered aspect of the @{" 'Prefs' " LINK  "Prefs"} window.
	The new gadgets are understood immediatly.

	    2) Now, saving the preferences also saves the current
	positions of all the windows.

	    3) Ital now recognises AmigaGuide files. @{" (See Prefs/Generali) " LINK "Prefs"}

	    4) Ital is able to be interrupted during a translation
	of entire directories by clicking the close gadget in the
	window.

	    5) Ital recognizes other @{" Key-Words " LINK "ParoleChiave"}, as suggested by @{b}Rocco
	Colluccelli@{ub}, from which I found the very convenient
	key-word 'Utente' ('user'). For example: If from the CLI
	(or from DirOpus) Ital is started with the command "Ital
	Utente", Ital, after starting, goes straight to the
	"Traduci una frase" ("Translate a phrase").


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Premessa"

	    @{b}Introduction to Automatic Translation.@{ub}

	    Automatic translation is one of the oldest and
	difficult problems facing information science. In the
	military and civilian sectors, linguists, researchers,
	and staffs of professional programmers of every nation
	have dedicated themselves to this problem.

	    The difficulty resides in the fact that translating a
	language is not always a science, in many cases it is
	considered an art. If it is an art, then the human
	researcher can never be replaced by the computer.

	    However, the translation made with the computer,
	despite of the errors and inelegance, have two great
	advantages: speed and low cost.

	    The advantages are augmented for those (like us) who
	already have the file we want translated in ASCII file
	format. It is also augmented by the fact that we want
	only to obtain a translation to get the gist of
	the subject matter. Subsequently, as time permits, we can proofread it
	for a more accurate translation.

	    The many "docs", "Read.me", "You_Must_Read_This", etc
	that normally accompany commercial, Shareware, and
	Freeware Programs for the Amiga are already, fortunately,
	in ASCII file format. With Ital, we can take these files
	and change them into something that most Italians can read.

	So Ital can not work miracles, but it does help a lot!


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Introduzione"

	    @{b}Introduction to Ital.@{ub}

	    As already said above, from the birth of the first
	computer there has been a search to create a complete
	translation program but the results did not satisfy the hopes.
	Well known, then, is the problem to face.
	Expecting these problems and the easy
	criticism that will arise with any translation program
	released, we have decided to write Ital. Not with a super
	computer that is used in Japan or America, but with an
	A500, 2 megs of Ram and 20MB harddrive.

	    Our A500 was not a super computer with megs and megs
	of RAM and a tremendous Harddrive. But, no other computer
	was able to provide an environment so stable and
	with a true multitasking for such a project. The Amiga is
	not affected with the problems of memory or graphics like
	when you program on other platforms. Also, with AREXX
	(something not available elsewhere) we can check the
	English words with Thesaurus and Transpell, have under
	control grammar and syntax with ProperGrammar, as well as to
	effectively cross research with various dictionaries.

	    To work on Ital has truly been enthusiastic. It has
	been an hard work involving research, study and
	programming, and it is in a constant state of improvement.
	The result of our experiment, to our modest satisfaction,
	has been outstanding. You can translate a 40,000 byte
	file (about 30 type written pages) in 2 seconds on an
	A4000/040. You will receive a document that for the most
	part can be understood in Italian. Our work was not in
	vain.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "ShareIt"

	@{b}Ital ShareWare Version and Ital Registered Version.@{ub}

	    Ital is ShareWare.
	    Do not look for a registered or commercial version, it does not exist!

	    As for Shareware Programs, you are able to copy and
	spread Ital as you like: As long as you don't try to make a
	profit and is not included on any commercial product
	without the consent of the author.

	    The author gives his permission to spread
	the program to the users who use it regularly (whether
	for work or amusement). There however comes the request,
	actually a "moral obligation", of the regular user to
	send a ShareWare contribution of 30,000 lire (about
	$15.00). This is a modest contribution and is absolutely
	voluntary and it expresses true gratitude for the work
	done.

	    Some ShareWare programs are distributed as Crippled
	programs, requiring the user to send payment for a
	complete version. This does not apply to Ital. For the
	moment, Ital remains a study project, or experiment so to
	speak, for fun. However, contributions are welcome. We
	want to see that the program is appreciated. It will also
	serve as an incentive to further improve Ital so as not
	to disappoint our friends (and we underline friends).

	    For Ital, the ShareWare contribution also serves as
	an incentive to develop a good translating program ported
	for the first generation of RISC Amigas.

	    The ShareWare fee is quoted above, the address of the
	author can be found here: @{" autore " LINK "INDIRIZZI"}.
	Don't forget to include your address when you write!

@ENDNODE

