@NODE "WORKBENCH"

	    @{b}Ital from the WorkBench:@{ub}

	    When started, Ital tries to load the file ItalVoc3.01
	(the dictionary), then, in a few moments (on the Amiga 4000
	instantaneously) tries to create the list in Ram to speed
	up the time it takes to translate.

	    Ital tries moreover to load the file @{" ItalPrefs " LINK "SALVA"},
	searching in the current directoy; in case
	it is not found, then it tries to search the S:
	directory.

	    If the said file is not found, Ital tells you then
	loads the default @{" Prefs " LINK "PREFS"}.

	    Ital's window presents you with 5 gadget:



	    See Also:

	    @{" Carica " LINK "Carica"} @{" Prefs " LINK "PREFS"}
	@{" Utente " LINK "Utente"} @{"  Ital  " LINK "Ital"} @{" Fine  " LINK "Fine"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CLI"

	    @{b}Ital from CLI:@{ub}

	    To launch the program from the Cli it is enough to
	type: Ital

	    or:  >Ital <name-of-the-file-to-translate>

	    For example:

	    You want to translate the file Pippo in the df0:docs
	directory.


	    >Ital df0:docs/Pippo

	    The program will then create the file
	Df0:Docs/Pippo.TRA.

	    See also: @{" Key-Word." LINK "ParoleChiave"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "AREXX"

	@{b}Ital & Arexx:@{ub}

	    The AREXX commands what Ital can receive and follow
	are those corresponding to the  @{" Key-Words." LINK  "ParoleChiave"}

	    A few friends have found it difficult to use
	Arexx, so we try now to explain step by step how to
	access the Arexx port in Ital.

	    First of all, we suggest learning the specific arguments
	and commands with your system manuals.
	You can also easily find ARexx tutorials in any magazine
	dedicated to the Amiga.

	    Take a look at the Arexx scripts contained in the
	Arexx drawer of the Ital archive.

	    As long as Ital is able to be commanded via Arexx
	they must satisfy the following conditions:

	    1) First of all, RexxMast must be activated.

	    (The RexxMast program is a way to open and utilize a
	port named "REXX". Through this port, programs can
	communicate to each other through their own Arexx ports.
		If RexxMast is not activated, then your programs
	cannot talk to each other.
		It is a good idea to drop the RexxMast program
	in your WBStartup drawer and leave it there permanently.
	So you will not have to ever think about opening this port.

	    2) Next, after you are sure that RexxMast is active,
	start Ital.  If Ital signals "Porta Arexx attivata"
	Ital's Arexx port is active and ready to be used.
	Instead if Ital signals "Porta Arexx disattivata", you
	need to select @{" Prefs/Preferenze Generali " LINK "PREFS"}
	of Ital and acctivate the option "Abilita porta
	Arexx". Then click on the button "Use". (You are also
	able to select, obviously, "Save". This makes sure that
	the next time you start Ital you won't have to reactivate
	the port. See also @{" Key-Word." LINK "ParoleChiave"}).


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Carica"

	    @{b}Gadget "Carica":@{ub}

	    The load gadget.

	    Selecting this gadget opens a file requestor where
	you are able to select the files to translate.  They must
	be in ASCII format. They may also be compacted with
	@{b}PowerPacker@{ub}.

	    Through the file requestor, you can select all the
	files of the working directory. You can also multiselect
	files in the same directory by holding down the Shift key
	and clicking on as many files as you want. After you
	select the file/s to translate, another requestor appears
	asking you where to save the .TRA files to.

	    The translated files are saved with the same name
	along with the extension .TRA.

	    The original files are NOT overwritten.

	    It is possible to save the translated file
	PowerPacked with the @{b}powerpacker.library@{ub} if it
	is activated in the @{" Prefs/Generali." LINK "PREFS"}

	    To read the translated files you should use any Text
	Viewer, Word-Processor or Text-Editor, remember if it is
	PowerPacked to use an Editor that supports those files
	such as @{b}View 80@{ub} (a beautiful Text-Reader made in
	Italy!), PPMore etc.

	    Make sure that there is enough space on your disk to
	save the translated files. Of course, if there isn't,
	the file won't be saved!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "PREFS"



	@{b}Gadget "Prefs":@{ub}


	    Clicking this button opens the "PREFERENZE"
	(Preferences) window where you see the following buttons:

		  @{"  Generali  (General) " LINK "GENERALI"}
		  @{"  Directory di lavoro (Work Directory) " LINK "WORKDIR"}
		  @{"  Vocabolari  (Dictionary) " LINK "VOCS"}
		  @{"  Ottimizzazioni  (Optimizations) " LINK "OTTIM"}
		  @{"  Font=ScreenFont " LINK "FONTS"}
		  @{"  Salva (Save) " LINK "SALVA"}@{"   Usa (Use)  " LINK "USA"}@{" Annulla (Cancel) " LINK "ANNULLA"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "GENERALI"

	    In the "@{b}PREFERENZE GENERALI@{ub}"
	"General Preferences" you see a series of CheckBoxes with which
	you can enable/disable the following options:

	    1) @{b}Abilita Porta Arexx@{ub} (Activate Arexx Port)

	    To activate/deactivate the Arexx port named "ITAL";

	    2) @{b}Abilita traduzione AmigaGuide@{ub} (Able to
	translate AmigaGuide)

	    When this option is enabled, Ital checks if the file
	to translate is in AmigaGuide format and then translates
	it, respecting AmigaGuide symbols and format.

	    If this option is disabled the AmigaGuide files will
	be translated like a normal ASCII file.

	    3) @{b}Salva con compressione PowerPacker@{ub} (Save
	as a PowerPacker file)

	    Ital is able to load a crunched PowerPacker file into
	memory then translate it.

	    Activating this option causes the file you are
	translating to be packed before it is saved.

	    @{b}ATTENTION!@{ub} The AmigaGuide program does not
	recognise compacted files; in such a case you need some
	other program which reads powerpacked AmigaGuide files,
	such as "@{b}ppguide@{ub}" and a few others that can be
	found on the Aminet.

	    4) @{b}Copia Icona@{ub} (Copy Icon)

	    Ital, with this option selected, will save a copy of
	an icon identical to the original file.

	    5) @{b}Salva con lung. linee max col=XX@{ub} (Save
	with long. Max Lines=XX)

	    This script is a bit obscure, but it means:

	    "Before saving the file, try to reformat the length
	of the lines in a style not longer than XX characters."

	    You assign XX to fit properly on your screen. The
	default is 80 characters in order to have good
	viewing on most systems.

	    6) @{b}Abilita Ing/Ita@{ub} (Activate Ing/Ita)

	    Not available at the moment.

	    7) @{b}Produci file di controllo@{ub}

	    Not available at the moment.

	    8) @{b}Mostra rapporto sulla velocitŕ@{ub} (Show
	report on the speed)

	    Activating this option, after you have translated an
	entire directory, allows Ital to show the total time it
	took to translate, the number of total bytes, and the speed
	of the translation in bytes per second.

	    The calculations above do not contain, obviously,
	the time which the file was loaded/saved.

	    While it is not very useful to users,
	it is very important to us in order to have under control
	the efficiency, in terms of speed, of the translation algorithms,
	so we can test our modifications and improvements.

	    We can also check the speed of a system before and
	after, for example, the installation of a memory
	expansion or an accelerator card. A kind of benchmark
	option, so to speak.

	    9) @{b}AppMenů@{ub}

	    When activated, you will see a new menu in the
	Workbench "Tools".  If you want to translate a file you
	have to first select the file to translate by clicking on
	its icon ONE TIME, then select "Ital" from the
	Workbench's "Tools" menu.

	    10) @{b}AppWindow@{ub}

	    Is similar to the Appmenu: you can translate a file,
	from the Workbench, simply by dragging the file's icon on
	Ital's window.

	    11) @{b}Chiedi directory di salvataggio@{ub} (Ask for
	the Save Directory)

	    Normally the translated file is saved in the same
	directory as the original.

	    Activating this gadget, before saving any file,
	causes Ital to open up a requestor so you can choose a
	different location in which to save the file.

	    12) @{b}Chiedi conferma prima di terminare@{ub} (Ask
	before closing)

	    Activating this CheckBox, Ital will always ask
	permission before closing.

	    @{b}Gadget 'Usa'@{ub} (Use)

	    All the preference modifications will be used by
	Ital.

	    @{b}Gadget 'Annulla'@{ub} (Cancel)

	    All the preference modifications to those options
	will not be used.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "WORKDIR"


	@{b}Gadget "Directory di lavoro" (Work Directory)@{ub}

	    Pressing this gadget opens a file requestor with
	which you can select a directory.

	    This allows you to define the eventual default
	directory, where you usually keep the files to translate.
	If you do not define a default directory, you will be
	presented with the RAM: directory.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "FONTS"


	@{b}Gadget "font=Screen_font/System_font"@{ub}

	    The graphic interface of Ital is font-sensitive, with
	regards to the length and height of the window, the
	gadgets and buttons are automatically modified to adapt
	to the selected font.

	    You can manipulate Ital's fonts using: "Screen font"
	and "System Font" which you can find in the "Font"
	program in the "Prefs" directory of the Workbench.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "UTENTE"


	@{b}Gadget "Utente"@{ub} (Utility)

	    Clicking this gadget opens a window titled "Prova a
	tradurre una frase!" ("Try to translate a phrase!")

	    This option is was implemented to test, on our part,
	the translation algorithms in an easy and fast way.

	    This great little utility is able to allow you, we
	imagine, to have a bit of amusement and to harass Ital.

	    Besides the amusement, if you find any error with the
	translation algorythm of Ital, please write us. But, don't
	write just to say "Ital should translate better!", but
	instead write this phrase into an ASCII file, save the file
	on a disk, and send it to us!

	    NOTE: When you insert a phrase, pay attention to the
	punctuation! Try to translate, for example, the following phrases,
	with the comma and question mark (correctly) and then
	without the comma and question mark (incorrectly).


	  - You are the King, aren't you?
	  - They can not go out, can they?


	    Or, if you search the meaning of a verb, gerund, or
	noun, use the article and or personal pronoun; so, for
	example, you can see the difference between the meanings of
	the words "work" and "work" depending on context.

	Look at the following example:

    1)  My work.	[work= "lavoro" (noun)]
	It works.	 [work= verb "lavorare")

	    The same goes with the big difference between "write"
	(the noun) and "write" (the verb).  For example:

    2) This is a nice writing.  [writing= "scrittura" (sostantivo)]
       I am writing a letter.   [writing= voce del verbo "scrivere"]

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ITAL"



	@{b}Gadget "Ital"@{ub}

	    To display some brief information about the program
	and the author.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FINE"



	@{b}Gadget "Fine"@{ub}

	    To say good-bye to Ital.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ParoleChiave"

	@{b}Parole-chiave:@{ub} (Key-Word)

	    The key words are particular commands which kindly
	invite Ital to do some interesting things.

	    There are eleven commands (key-words) recognized by
	Ital plus the Wildcard, and they are able to be
	passed to Ital through the CLI or through Arexx. They
	are:

    @{"  UTENTE  " LINK "UTENTE"}   @{"  SCREEN=  " LINK "SCREEN"}   @{"   ZIP   " LINK "ZIP"}   @{"  SPLIT  " LINK "SPLIT"}   @{"  CLEAR  " LINK "CLEAR"}
    @{"   ITAL   " LINK "ITAL"}   @{"  SAVEDIR= " LINK "SAVEDIR"}   @{"  UNZIP  " LINK "UNZIP"}   @{" NOSPLIT " LINK "NOSPLIT"}   @{" * (asterisk) " LINK "ASTERISCO"}
    @{"   QUIT   " LINK "QUIT"}   @{"  NOSKIP   " LINK "NOSKIP"}

	    The command line, inserted from the CLI, is examined
	word for word. If Ital doesn't recognize any of the
	key-words, it will be assumed that you have entered the
	name of a file. So, be careful when you type!

	    Example from the CLI:

    >Ital SAVEDIR=RAM: df0:myfile CLEAR df2:PackMan.doc QUIT

	    With the above line, Ital will examine each word one
	at a time:


    - with SAVEDIR you tell Ital to save the output to RAM:
    - translate the df0:myfile and save it to RAM:
    - with CLEAR you return Ital back to save in the default directory
    - translate the file df2:PackMan.doc and save it to df2:
    - with QUIT you terminate Ital.

If you were to do the same thing with an AREXX script:

    [......]

    address 'ITAL'

    'SAVEDIR=RAM:'  /* Key-Word + Directory !without spaces! */

    'df0:myfile' /*If it's not a key-word, then it's a name of a file*/

    'CLEAR'	      /*  Key-Word. */

    'df2:PackMan.doc'    /*  Name of a file. */

    'QUIT'	       /*  Key-Word. */

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SAVEDIR"


	@{b}SAVEDIR@{ub}

	    You can use the keyword SAVEDIR= to select the
	directory where to save the translated files.

	    This can be used, for example, when you want to save
	to a different directory than the default.  Such a
	directory can obviously be different than the original
	directory.  The name of the file will be, like always,
	the same as the original, with the suffix ".TRA" added to
	it.

	    ATTENTION: until you give the command @{" CLEAR " LINK "CLEAR"}
	the directory you save to will always be
	that which you preselected with SAVEDIR=.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "SCREEN"


	@{b}SCREEN@{ub}

	    The window where Ital will open does not have to be
	just the Workbench, but on any active public screen.

	    You can specify, in the command line, the name
	of the screen, with the keyword: SCREEN=name-of-the-screen.

	    This is very useful, for example, when Ital is called
	to translate a file with DirOpus.

	    To add a menu/button to DirOpus, you only need to
	write:

	    "Work:Inglese/Varie/Ital SCREEN=DOPUS.1 {F} QUIT"

	    In such a case, Ital opens the her window on the
	DirOpus screen, translates the file selected with the
	mouse {F}, saves it, then exits because of the keyword
	@{" QUIT " LINK "QUIT"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOSKIP"


	@{b}NOSKIP@{ub}

	    If you use from the CLI the command:

	 > Ital Work:miadir/*

		       or:

	 > Ital MieiDocs:*

	    Ital translates @{b}all@{ub} the files contained in
	the directory miadir or on the disk MieiDocs,
	@{b}with exception@{ub} the files ending with:

	 .info (icon);
	 .bak  (copy or backup);
	 .TRA  (file already translated).

	    Well, with the keyword NOSKIP it will translate ALL
	the files in the directory/disk including the files
	mentioned above.

	    (A use quite rare and in fact is implemented only for
	our testing purposes.)

	    ATTENTION: NOSKIP will stay activated until you pass
	the command @{" CLEAR " LINK "CLEAR"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CLEAR"


	    @{b}CLEAR@{ub}

	    Using this key word to restore the program back to
	the default after using the @{" NOSKIP " LINK "NOSKIP"}
	or @{" SAVEDIR= " LINK "SAVEDIR"}, from which:

	    -NOSKIP allows Ital to translate the files ending in .info, .bak.
	The default is: DO NOT translate these files.

	    -SAVEDIR= allows Ital to save the translated files into a
	directory that is not the the original one.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "QUIT"


	@{b}QUIT@{ub}

	    This key-word will end Ital.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "ASTERISCO"


	    @{b}Use of the Asterisk (*)@{ub}

	    If Ital finds the asterisk immediatly after the name
	of a directory (after the slash) or on after the name of
	a disk (after the colon), it will translate all of the
	files inside that directory and all the sub-directories.

	    Examples:

    Ital Work:docs/*   (translates all the files in the Work:docs directory)
    Ital df1:*	 (translates all the files on the df1: disk)
    Ital ram:provv/*   (translates all the files in the directory ram:provv)


	    @{b}ATTENTION:@{ub}

	    The search is recursive, that is to say it searches in the
	specified directory and all of its sub-directories.  Ital
	then translates all the files in that directory and all
	the subdirectories.

	    In any case, Ital by default does NOT translate the
	files ending in .info, .bak e .TRA.

	    However, Ital can be interrupted during a translation
	of entire directories by clicking the close gadget in the
	window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SPLIT"


		@{b}SPLIT@{ub}

	    To reformat the saved file so that the length of lines is no longer
	    than a certain amount, chosen by you.
	    The default length is 80 characters.

	    See option no. 5) in @{" Prefs/Generali " LINK "Prefs"}.

	    See also @{" NOSPLIT " LINK "NOSPLIT"}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "NOSPLIT"


	    @{b}NOSPLIT@{ub}

	    To cancel the reformat option that considers the
	length of the line to translate.

	    See option  5) in @{" Prefs/Generali " LINK "Prefs"}.

	    See also @{" SPLIT " LINK "SPLIT"}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "ZIP"


	@{b}ZIP@{ub}

	    To 'zip' the window of Ital.

	    Try to send the Zip command to Ital:

	    	> Ital ZIP

	    See also @{" UNZIP " LINK "UNZIP"}.

	    (Note: 'ZIP' do not have any thing in common with the
	compression program of the same name).

@ENDNODE
@NODE "UNZIP"


	@{b}UNZIP@{ub}

	    To 'un-zipp' (enlarge) Ital's window..

	    See also @{" ZIP " LINK "ZIP"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "OTTIM"


	    @{b}Optimization@{ub}

	    We stop again here at the so called "optimizzazioni"
	(optimizations) available from the special buttons in the
	Prefs/Ottimizzazioni area of Ital and which Ital applies
	to the English file before translating.


	    These are:

	    1) Eliminate double spaces between the words;
	    2) Eliminate spaces attached to the end of lines;
	    3) Eliminate spaces at the beginning of the lines;
	    4) Eliminate tabs at the beginning of the lines;
	    5) Correct inverted commas;
	    6) Modify CR+LF=LF;
	    7) Eliminate spaces between punctuation;

	    All the optimizations are small and fast routines
	which work on examining and modifying the English files'
	punctuation.

	    Do you have a normal file .doc, with all the myriad
	of tabs, periods, commas, semi-colons, multiple spaces
	between words, words in upper or lower case, backwards
	commas, hyphens, quotes, frames, graphs etc??

	    Well, now you are able to understand how much work
	Ital has to do to understand the English text, also through the
	control of punctuation.

	    Correct punctuation is very important,
	so through the above said so-called 'optimization'
	(optimizing and correcting the file's punctuation),
	you have a better final translation.

	    If you make a file like these simple phrases:

     - This is an important question!
     - You have a black cat, haven't you?
     - We have decided to walk.
     - ONLY AMIGA MAKES IT POSSIBLE!

	    ... for as said above, @{b}don't@{ub}  forget to
	respect proper punctuation and in any case, to put at
	least a punctuation at the end of the phrase.  Something
	between: the period, exclamation point, question mark,
	comma, semi-colon, colon, which Ital uses to understand
	when the phrase is finished and allows things to be
	examined more deeply and, if possible, gives you a more
	correct translation.


@ENDNODE
@NODE "SALVA"


	@{b}Salva Preferenze@{ub}

	    Save Preferences.

	    Pressing the button 'SALVA' saves all the preferences
	in the file "@{b}S:ItalPrefs@{ub}", or in another you
	have selected. Keep in mind that when Ital starts, it
	tries to load the ItalPrefs file from the same directory
	where Ital and ItalVoc are located. In case the ItalPrefs
	file is not found in that directory it tries to load it
	from the S: directory.

	    Then (if what is said above is clear) you save the
	preferences in S: or in the same directory where there is
	Ital and ItalVoc.

	    In this version you may also save the position of
	Ital's windows (under Preferenze/Generali/Ottimizzazioni/Utente).
	The position saved are those that Ital finds when windows are first
	closed.


@ENDNODE
@NODE "USA"


	@{b}Usa@{ub} (Use)

	    The preferences you selected will be used for only this
	current session of work.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "ANNULLA"


	@{b}Annulla@{ub} (Cancel)

	    All the modifications you made will be cancelled.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "VOCS"


	@{b}Dictionaries@{ub}

	    Not available at the moment.


@ENDNODE

