@NODE "Requisiti"

	    @{b}Installation and Requirements for Ital:@{ub}

	    Ital requires Workbench 2.0 or above and can function
	from the disk or from the Hard Disk.

	    To work from a floppy only system it is enough to
	have just the Workbench with the ReqTools.library
	installed.

	    Ital 2.5 occupies about 450,000 bytes of memory. For
	those systems short on RAM (like a base A500 or A600) you
	will be seriously limited to the size of the file you can
	load.

	    To install Ital on Hard Disk it is enough to copy to
	any directory on your Hard Hardisk the following files
	using the CLI:

	    Ital, Ital.info (the icon), and ItalVoc.2.5.

	    Or, using the Workbench simply drag the "Ital.2.5"
	drawer wherever you want.


	    NOTE:

	    -Ital does not need a configuration file.

	    -Ital does require ReqTools.library.

	    -If you want to work with PowerPacked crunched files,
	then you need the PowerPacker.library installed in your
	Libs: directory.

	    - If you want to hear the phrase in English: push the
	requestor "Prova a tradurre una frase!" ( "Try to
	Translate a Frase!"). However, for this to work, you need
	the following system files installed:

	    1) "translator.library" in LIBS:,

	    2) "Narrator.device" in DEVS:

	    Warning! the translator.library and narrator.device
	(Copyright Commodore) strangely do not come installed
	with the new 2.0 version of Workbench. For those who do
	not have them already on your Workbench you must get
	ahold of some old pre-2.0 software and copy it over.

	    NOTE: The DosDriver "Speak" and the "Speak-handler"
	are no longer needed for this feature to work (as in the
	previous versions of Ital). Now, Ital will access the
	narrator.device directly.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Collaborazioni"

	@{b}Collaborations:@{ub}

	    Ital is continually being updated, in the time
	available according to the suggestions I receive.

	    The updates of the dictionary, the correction of
	errors, the updates to new rules, etc., come from the
	reading and studying of various translated files and are
	compared to the original files in English, searching on
	general ways to change the algorythm.

	    If you have any suggestions, please write!

	    To make your suggestions for better translations, you should
	try always to understand the original English file: if it's not
	written in correct English, the problem is with the
	grammar and/or syntax (for example, "its" instead of "it's").
	While those written in proper English could be written,
	for example, in Ancient English or is using poetic form. It
	could even be use written in slang like you'll find in
	English/American songs.

	    We will be grateful for ALL suggestions.  Above all
	it we are more grateful when you send these examples and
	problem in English, on disk, as an ASCII file.

	    We suggest the most effective way to send these
	suggestions:

------------------------

	    Dear Arturo,

	    I have prepared an ASCII file for you on this disk. I
	have prepared some phrases in English taken from my
	grammar book and from a short story by Agatha Christie
	(so you will be dead sure these phrases are written in proper English!)
	that was not translated well by Ital.

	    The errors I found were with the verb 'to like' and
	with that particular verb 'to be', and some idioms used
	frequently.

	    I propose and suggest....  (or, I don't propose
	anything. Look at it, and good luck!).

------------------------

	    To send a disk costs little, 1850 lire in stamps plus
	about 500 lire for a good envelope. But, it is the typing
	that is which costs the most.

	    In short, for us it is most important that there is a
	disk. If you send a file or phrase in English in ASCII
	format, it allows us to test the file immediatly,
	comparing it to other English files that we are working
	on to correct and improve.

	    If you send general rule of English that we might be
	able to implement to improve our translations, don't
	hesitate to write! Put it on a disk any information you
	believe will help Ital to translate English better.




@ENDNODE

